# Project: Classify Breast Cancer using SVM

import numpy as np

Let's first load the breast cancer dataset provided by the University of Wisconsin. Features are computed from a digitized image of a fine needle aspirate (FNA) of a breast mass. They describe characteristics of the cell nuclei present in the image.

In [2]:
#Load breast cancer data from University of Wisconsin
(X, y) = load_breast_cancer(return_X_y=True, as_frame=True) # as_frame argument provides data as Pandas dataframe

There are 30 attributes and 569 instances. None of the data points is missing and the data set is complete. The dataset that we can find in scikit-learn has already been cleaned. The original dataset in the UCI repository instead included some missing data.

The target variable has only two classes. 0 indicates that the cancer is malignant, 1 indicates that it is benign. The dataset is also slightly imbalanced, with more than 2/3 of the samples relative to the class 1.

Preparing the data to train the model¶

After exploring some of the data characteristics, we are ready to prepare our dataset to train our machine learning algorithm. In this case we chose to split the dataset with an 80/20 ratio for train and test. This ratio is quite common in machine learning. We also set the seed to a fixed number to provide reproducibility.

In [12]:
#Split data into train and test set (80-20)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = .2, shuffle=True, random_state = 77)
In [13]:
cnt = y_train.value_counts()
print(f'Train set target ratio: {cnt[0]/cnt[1]}')

Train set target ratio: 0.6134751773049646
In [14]:
cnt = y_test.value_counts()
print(f'Test set target ratio: {cnt[0]/cnt[1]}')

Test set target ratio: 0.52

As we can see above, the resulting train and test sets are not balanced. The ratio between target classes is different (61% vs 52%). This might be an issue for the training of the model, so we decide to utilize the 'stratify' option provided by scikit-learn.

In [15]:
#Split data into train and test set (80-20) with STRATIFICATION
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = .2, 
                                                    shuffle=True, random_state = 77,
                                                    stratify=y)
In [16]:
cnt = y_train.value_counts()
print(f'Train set target ratio: {cnt[0]/cnt[1]}')

Train set target ratio: 0.5964912280701754
In [17]:
cnt = y_test.value_counts()
print(f'Test set target ratio: {cnt[0]/cnt[1]}')

Test set target ratio: 0.5833333333333334

After the split with stratification, the ratio of the target classes in the train and test datasets now is closer.

Classification using Support Vector Machine (SVM)¶

At this point, we are ready to train our model. We choose to utilize a Support Vector Machine (SVM) for this project. SVM is a good option when the target is binary as in this case.

In [18]:
# SVM model with Radial Basis Function kernel
clf = SVC() # By default, kernel='RBF'
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on test set
y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)

# Calculate classification accuracy
score_train = clf.score(X_train, y_train) 
score_test = clf.score(X_test, y_test)
print(f"SVM train score: {score_train} | test score: {score_test}")

SVM train score: 0.9230769230769231 | test score: 0.9122807017543859

With the default kernel (Radial Basis Function), we can already obtain a good score (91%). We can also plot the confusion matrix to check how many examples our model couldn't classify correctly.

In [19]:
confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
Out[19]:
array([[34,  8],
       [ 2, 70]], dtype=int64)
In [23]:
plot_confusion_matrix(clf, X_test, y_test)

Let's see now if we can improve the model performance. When we explored the data, from the scatterplots we noticed that most of the features could be linearly separated to provide information towards the target variable. We can see if this intuition can be used to improve the performance, and thus use a linear kernel to train the SVM model.

In [26]:
# SVM model with linear kernel
clf = SVC(kernel='linear')
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on test set
y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)

# Calculate classification accuracy
score_train = clf.score(X_train, y_train) 
score_test = clf.score(X_test, y_test)
print(f"SVM train score: {score_train} | test score: {score_test}")

SVM train score: 0.9692307692307692 | test score: 0.956140350877193
In [28]:
plot_confusion_matrix(clf, X_test, y_test)
plt.grid(False)

Using a linear kernel, our test score improved by more than 4% to 95.6%. We can see that the train score is higher than the test score (96.9% vs 95.6%). This denotes some overfitting to the train data. In the next section, we can see if we can improve this.

Dimensionality reduction with Principal Component Analysis (PCA)¶

Using Principal Component Analysis (PCA), we can check if some of the input features are more important than others (i.e. if they carry more information).

In [29]:
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)
In [30]:
# Principal Component Analysis
pca = PCA()
pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)
pca_variance = pca.explained_variance_

# Visualize principal components
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.bar(range(len(pca_variance)), pca_variance, alpha=0.5, align='center', label='individual variance')
plt.legend()
plt.ylabel('Variance ratio')
plt.xlabel('Principal components')
plt.show()
In [31]:
# Explained variance ratio of first 16 components
sum(pca_variance[0:16])/sum(pca_variance)
Out[31]:
0.9891502160796992

As we can see above, the first 16 components already provide almost 99% of all the variance. The remaining 14 components do not bring any new information, because they are lowly correlated to the output or because they are linearly correlated with other input features. We can thus keep only the first 16 components of the dataset and discard the rest. This way we eliminated almost half of the input data that is not strictly needed.

In [32]:
pca = PCA(n_components=16)
X_reduced = pca.fit(X_scaled).transform(X_scaled)
In [33]:
#Split data into train and test set (80-20) with STRATIFICATION
X_train_reduced, X_test_reduced, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_reduced, y, test_size = .2, 
                                                    shuffle=True, random_state = 77,
                                                    stratify=y)
In [34]:

SVM train score: 0.9846153846153847 | test score: 0.9824561403508771

After retraining the SVM model with the reduced and normalized dataset, the performance is greatly improved. Both the train and test score are 98% denoting practically no overfitting to the train data. The confusion matrix shows that only 2 examples (1 per category) are misclassified out of a total of 114.
